Factors influencing the rental bid of hawker stalls

19 June 2021

1. Hawker stall rental analysis

1.1 Problem Statement

During last December 2020, Singapores Hawker Culture was acknowledged as part of UNESCO Representative List of the Intangible Cultural of Humanity. This acknowledgment aptly reinforced Singapore as being a multicultural city as it reflects our multicultural identity as a people and nation, that resonates strongly with all Singaporeans across all races and social strata.

Since then, there are more younger Singaporeans who are willing to embark into this hawker culture, bringing in affordable fusion and international food, while adding a bit of spice and novelty to the various local delicacies from the different races.

For a person interested to venture into this scene, there will be a need to decide what type of hawker trade to embark on and the location of hawker stall to rent out, before submitting the tender bid through the National Environment Agency (NEA). NEA will offer monthly tender notices to the public on available hawker stalls for rental and specifies the location and type of trade/products allowed. Interested applicants will need to undergo a bidding process. NEA will then award the hawker stall to the tenderer with the highest rental bid.

For our capstone project, we are interested to examine the factors that influence the rental bid of hawker stalls, specifically:

  • How stall size affect the tendered rental bid and whether the accessibility to the hawker stall alters this relationship

  • How stall type (cooked food, locked-up and market stall) affects the tendered rental bid and whether the location of the hawker stall alters this relationship. In this context, locked-up stall refers to stalls that provides services or dried goods. Market stall in general refers to stalls that sells fresh produce.

1.2 Import

The project will require the usage of data from the National Environmental Agency (NEA) on the list of successful tendered stalls per month, from March 2012 to March 2021. This will be supplemented with other data sources from readily available APIs and web scraping from websites.

  • List of Successsful Tendered Rental Bids from 2012 to 2021 in csv format
  • List of Government Markets Hawker Centres from NEA API
  • Latitude and Longitude of hawker stalls from OneMap API
  • Regions that hawker stall is located, i.e.Central or Non-Central. As a proxy, we will rely on the classification used for properties, by webscraping from propertyguru website
  • List of MRT in Singapore from Dataworld in csv format
  • List of Bus Stops in Singapore from the LTA Bus Stops API
  • List of Carparks in Singapore from the HDB website

The data have been cleaned, merged and saved in successful_bids_df.csv.

To initiate our analysis, we activated the following packages, using the Tidyverse approach.

pacman::p_load(tidyverse)

1.3 Basic Visualization

To gain a better understanding of our data, we will create plots with basic visualization from the dataset. We plot the location of the hawker stalls with respect to the tendered rental bid.

pacman::p_load(leaflet)
successful_bids_df %>%
  leaflet() %>%

    lng = 103.8198,

                                            ifelse(tendered_bid_per_month < 2000, "orange",

             stroke = TRUE,
             fillOpacity = 0.8) %>% 
  addLegend("bottomright", 
            colors = c("white","yellow","green","orange","red"),
            labels = c("Below $500","$500-$1000","$1000-$1500","$1500-$2000","Above $2500"),
            title = "Tendered Rental Bids")

Here, it appears that hawker stalls are concentrated in the central, west, south and eastern regions of Singapore. On average, most of the hawker stalls have tendered rental bid of less than $1500, although there were a few with higher rental bids.

1.4 Tidy & Transform

For creation of the model, the variable tendered_bid_per_month will serve as our dependent Y variable. The independent X variables are stall_area_sqm,stall_type,hc_region,hc_dist_to_mrt,hc_dist_to_bus and hc_dist_to_carpark.

The first thing we did with our loaded dataset was to combine the three variables (hc_dist_to_mrt,hc_dist_to_bus, hc_dist_to_carpark) into two variables (min_dist_public_trnspt, min_dist_private_trnspt) which specifies the minimum distance from hawker stall to a public or private transport, in order to gauge accessibility. We also re-coded the stall_type and hc_region variables into binary variables (cooked, central), which specifies whether the stall sells cooked or non-cooked food and whether the stall is in central or non-central region.

successful_bids_df <- successful_bids_df %>% 
  mutate(min_dist_public_trnspt = rowMeans(successful_bids_df %>%
                                             select(hc_dist_to_mrt,
                                                    hc_dist_to_bus)),
         min_dist_private_trnspt = hc_dist_to_carpark,
         cooked = case_when(stall_type %in% c("locked_up_stalls",
                                              "market_stalls") ~ 0,
                            stall_type == "cooked_food_stalls" ~ 1),
         central = case_when(hc_region %in% c("Rest of Central Region", 
                                              "Outside Central Region") ~ 0,
                             hc_region == "Core Central Region" ~ 1),
         tendered_bid = round(tendered_bid_per_month))

1.5.1 Main Effects Only

We then ran two regression models. The first model with main effects regressed stall size, location and accessibility onto tendered rental bid (ols_main). As the continuous data are right skewed, we also attempted the models with main effects using log transformation (ols_main_log) and square root transformation (ols_main_sqrt).

\[ \begin{eqnarray} \widehat{tendered\_bid} = intercept + b_1stall\_area + b_2min\_dist\_public\_trnspt + \\b_3min\_dist\_private\_trnspt + b_4cooked + b_5central + \epsilon \end{eqnarray} \]

ols_main <- lm(tendered_bid ~ stall_area_sqm + min_dist_public_trnspt + min_dist_private_trnspt 
               + cooked + central,
               data = successful_bids_df)

1.5.2 With Interaction

Our key investigation lies in the next model (ols_interact), in which we regressed stall size, location and accessibility along with interaction terms onto life satisfaction. We also attempted the models using log transformation (ols_interact_log) and square root transformation (ols_interact_sqrt) as the data is right skewed.

\[ \begin{eqnarray} \widehat{tendered\_bid} = intercept + b_1stall\_area + b_2min\_dist\_public\_trnspt + b_3min\_dist\_private\_trnspt + b_4cooked + \\b_5central + b_7stall\_area \times min\_dist\_public\_trnspt + b_8stall\_area \times in\_dist\_private\_trnspt + \epsilon \end{eqnarray} \]

ols_interact <- 
  lm(tendered_bid ~ 
       stall_area_sqm * (min_dist_public_trnspt + min_dist_private_trnspt) +
       cooked + central,
     data = successful_bids_df)

1.5.3 Model Comparison

Adjusted R-squared

For the models with main effects ols_main,ols_main_log,ols_main_sqrt, the adjusted R-squared are 0.400, 0.359 and 0.438 respectively.

For the models with interaction ols_interact,ols_interact_log,ols_interact_sqrt, the adjusted R-squared are 0.402, 0.363 and 0.441 respectively.

Compared to the models with main effects, the adjusted R-squared of the corresponding models with interaction terms are higher. This suggests that adding the interaction terms improves the explanatory power of the model.

ANOVA

We also compared the models using ANOVA.

In general, VIF of more than 4 will be an issue as it undermines the statistical significance of an independent variable.

From the results, the VIF of models with main effects are less than 4, hence there are no concerns.

As for the models with interaction effects, VIF of more than 4 are produced. However, this could be because interaction terms are created from the independent variables. Therefore, we will not be removing any of the variables from the model in our subsequent steps.

Unfortunately, the results show that the assumptions of linearity are not satisfied for the OLS models that we have created to investigate if the stall size affects the tendered rental bid. Hence, we will not move on with our second investigation on whether stall type (cooked) affects the tendered rental bid using OLS.

Instead, we turned to Poisson regression model as it can account for non-linear relationships between the Y and X variables.

1.6 Poisson Regression Model

1.6.1 Main Effects

We ran two Poisson Regression models. The first model with main effects regressed stall size, location and accessibility onto tendered rental bid (poisson_main).

poisson_main <- 
glm(tendered_bid ~ stall_area_sqm + min_dist_public_trnspt + 
      min_dist_private_trnspt + cooked + central,
    family="poisson",
    data = successful_bids_df)

                            min_dist_public_trnspt + min_dist_private_trnspt,

1.7 Interpretation of the Results

From our data science project, we have deduce the following:

  1. The relationships between the stall size and the tendered rental bid depends on the accessibility of the hawker stall. Specifically, hawker stalls which are very accessible by public transport seems to garner a higher tendered bid for larger stall sizes. On the contrary, hawker stalls which are very accessible by private transport seems to garner a lower tendered rental bid for larger stall size. As the results are correlational, further investigation with a/b testing should follow to ascertain a causal relationship.

  2. The relationships between stall type and tendered bid per month also depends on the location. It appears that cooked food stalls which are centrally located has higher tendered bid as compared to cooked food stalls which are not centrally located. Similarly, non-cooked food stalls which are centrally located has a higher tendered bid as compared to stalls that are not centrally located. Again, as the results are correlational, further investigation with a/b testing should follow to ascertain a causal relationship.

1.8 Implications

Relationship between tendered rental bids and stall size, whether the accessibility to public/private transport alters the relationship

Based on the model visualization, for stalls that are greater than 13 square metres, the tendered rental bid shows an upward trend as stall size increases. This observation could be attributed to the fact that bidders are more likely to place a much higher bid price for a stall that is accessible by people due to the convenience of buses and MRTs located nearby. With a larger crowd, there would be a higher tendency for people to patronize the stalls and enticing people to buy the food sold in the stalls. With that, the stall owner would gain more profit as there is greater demand for the food. For those stalls that are not accessible by public transport, the tendered bids were lower. This could be due to the fact that these bidders do not foresee a large crowd patronizing the stalls due to its inaccessibility, hence it may not be prudent to bid a high price for the stalls.

However, for stalls that are smaller than 13 square metres, the tendered bids for rental seem to suggest bidders are more likely to bid higher amount for stalls that are inaccessible by public transport. A further analysis is required to investigate if there are other factors causing this observation.

On the contrary, for stalls that are accessible by private transport, the variance between stalls that are very accessible compared to stalls that are inaccessible differs greatly. The highest tendered bid for rental for accessible places by private transport accounts for merely $800, compared to the highest tendered bid for rental for inaccessible places of approximately $1,300. This could be due to the fact that some stalls categorised under very accessible to private transport could be inaccessible to public transports. Hence, the bidders are likely to bid a lower price as they could be under the impression that other bidders are unlikely to compete with them for these stalls. Similarly, those stalls categorised under not accessible to private transport could be accessible to public transport which resulted in a much higher tendered bids. Further investigation is necessary to support our conjecture.

Relationship between tendered rental bids and stall type, whether the location of stall affects the relationship

The graph illustrates a much higher tendered bid for rental of stalls that are selling cooked food in the central region. For non-cooked food stalls located in the non-central region, they garnered the lowest tendered bid for rental of hawker stalls. For non-cooked stalls, the tendered bids for rental are relatively lower for both central and non-central regions. Such observations may be due to the assumption made by the bidders that there will be little competition from other bidders who are planning to sell non-cooked food to the consumers, hence it may not be wise for them to bid a high price to secure the stalls.

For cooked-stalls, the tendered bids for rental in the central region is much higher than those in non-central regions. Due to a wide variety of cuisines sold in Singapore, there is stiff competition between hawkers to sell food that are appealing to the public. Therefore, in terms of cooked food, there is higher demand from the public which may possibly result in bidders placing a higher bid in order to secure the stalls.

1.9 Limitations and Future Directions

Though these data are obtained from NEAs website, it is worthy to note there are several terms and conditions for NEA to consider before selecting the tenderer for a particular stall. One of these terms and conditions states that The NEA does not bind itself to accept the highest or any offer at all and the decision of the NEA shall be final. Based on the above statement, perhaps the tendered bids for rental of hawker stalls does not reflect the true bid amount that won the tender for hawker stalls. There may be a lack of transparency on how these tendered bids are selected, hence affecting the accuracy of the data published on NEAs website.

In addition, the tendered bids for rental of hawker stalls do not reflect the true costs of operating a hawker stall. These hidden costs include the service and conservancy charge, refuse removal fee, license fees, Goods and Services Tax (GST) and monthly charges such as water and electricity bills which could vary depending on the type of food sold for a hawker stall. While it may seem that the costs to operate a hawker centre is low based on the data, but one must note that there are other costs which could possibly increase the total costs of running a hawker stall.

Due to the above reasons, the analysis above based on the data obtained from NEA serves as a reference for future bidders who have plans to venture into opening a hawker stall. More data could be obtained from NEA to provide a holistic and accurate data analysis for the tendered bids for rental of hawker stalls.

It is also important to note that current analysis only look into the (1) Stall Size, (2) Distance to Public Transport and (3) Distance to Private Transport as the key variables that could affect the Tendered Rental Bid. Thus, it is recommended that the following variables be included in future analysis:

  • Vicinity to Residential, Maturity of Estate, Commercial (CBD, Non-CBD), Industrial Areas (Labour Intensive)

  • Ethnic Demography (eg. Chinatown, Little India, Geylang Serai, Holland Village, etc)

Another point to note is that the hawker centres dataset only reflects tendered rental bid for government-managed hawker stalls. Dataset could be expanded in future to include privately owned hawker stalls.
